    "Carroll & Parola, 2024; Ross & Ladyman, 2010).",
    "What Anscombe describes as a 'mistake' is only the attempt to compress the normative and teleological structure of action down to a single point of interaction between two constitutively distinct orders: cognitive internal processes and non-cognitive external events.",
    "Rather, as research on cognitive offloading suggests, it's at the level of this ubiquitous and transformative means of interacting with our shared environments that the distinctive shape of human cognitive agency comes into view.",
    "Combining this outlook with HEC has an unexpected upshot.",
    "It means we can evaluate putative cases of world-involving cognition by leaning on our practices of assigning responsibility."
